Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the US government represents an enormous bailout for the creditors of these institutions, whose losses had ballooned further in light of falling house prices.
Now that the government is completely stepping in for Fannie and Freddie's debts, American taxpayers will have to pay for everything that isn't covered by the inadequate financing of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in the most overtly capitalist country in the world?
Don't the venerable principles of capitalism include the notion that those who believed in the housing bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that now innocent taxpayers have to pay for their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly outlined.
But they are not.
Above all, it is unclear whether the bailout will actually cost US taxpayers in the end. It may possibly prevent further systemic effects that would force the financial sector and thus the world economy to its knees.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify, we cannot infer that they do not exist.
In addition, the bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as if they were equipped with an implicit guarantee of the US government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a rescue operation by the US government could undermine confidence in government securities and, because they are associated with them, also in other financial instruments.
The problems extend far beyond the US economy.
The global economy has been driven over the past few years by remarkable speculative highs and crashes of asset values, which brings in questions of trust, but also of fairness into the equation.
Similar height flights of the housing sector are coming to an end in many other countries as well, and they may be facing the same torments – and the same moral dilemmas – that the US economy is currently undergoing.
And the problem isn't just the housing markets.
The stock markets are it too.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of 5 between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose by a factor of five in real terms between 2003 and 2007, and has lost a third of its value since then.
Similar market crashes and stock market declines have occurred in many other countries.
As long as they held steady, the boom phases preceding these crashes led to overheating of these economies.
Now, having turned around, a decline in trust could engulf the global economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary – not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when help dries up in the face of collapsing markets.
The people's reactions to these events depend on their feelings and sense of justice.
The described altitude flights and crashes have caused a significant redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested on the stock exchange or on the housing market cut their returns well or poorly depending on the timing.
People will judge the fairness of these results based on what they were told and the implicit promises they inferred from it.
What was told to people in all these countries about the markets where they invested their money?
Was everything really true?
Unfortunately, there is no way to find out.
The politics can only react generally and not treat all cases individually.
We know that the economic growth of recent times has been spectacular in many countries.
But were the capital investments sold too expensive in their markets?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere enticed people into the assumption that boom times would bring prosperity for all?
It's certain that, although there may have been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – given, most of the losers in this game are not gnawing at the rag.
However, we cannot conclude from this that we should leave all their losses unchecked.
The nagging problem is one of "good faith".
Economies thrive only when "good faith" prevails.
The current situation, where speculative highs have driven the global economy – and now, following their collapse, are pushing it into recession –, suggests that people who have promoted certain investments have acted in bad faith.
Take the investors who have written Fannie and Freddie bonds.
Although the U.S. government never officially promised to bail them out in times of need, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to evaluate their strength in an annual report.
This agency, however, has never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
The government's top officials never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is in the process of transforming and discovering capitalism and its power to convert into economies of the people.
But capitalism relies on trust.
An unfair treatment perceived as such can be deadly for economic growth, because it means people lose their trust in companies and therefore are less willing to put their valuable assets and labor at their disposal.
Is such a result morally preferable to a bailout?
